<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/2DB7ED73-8E89-457A-A395-FAC12F929C1A"><gtr:id>2DB7ED73-8E89-457A-A395-FAC12F929C1A</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Edinburgh</gtr:name><gtr:department>Sch of Social and Political Science</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Old College</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>South Bridge</gtr:line2><gtr:line3>Mayfield Road</gtr:line3><gtr:line4>Edinburgh</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>EH8 9YL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/2DB7ED73-8E89-457A-A395-FAC12F929C1A"><gtr:id>2DB7ED73-8E89-457A-A395-FAC12F929C1A</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Edinburgh</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Old College</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>South Bridge</gtr:line2><gtr:line3>Mayfield Road</gtr:line3><gtr:line4>Edinburgh</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>EH8 9YL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/D3EE9865-41F3-4005-A0C1-86C0F662053D"><gtr:id>D3EE9865-41F3-4005-A0C1-86C0F662053D</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Meera</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Venkatachalam</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH002790%2F1"><gtr:id>7B9BF6CB-6E07-4474-86A8-DEE832738AE5</gtr:id><gtr:title>Slavery, Kinship and the Politics of Social Exclusion in south-eastern Ghana</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H002790/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The aim of this fellowship is to disseminate Venkatachalam's doctoral research, which examined how the memories and vestiges of the past practice of slave-holding amongst the Anlo-Ewe of south-eastern Ghana continue to persist in the contemporary socio-economic, political and religious landscape. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This project will seek to make a contribution to historical studies of slavery in Africa, by examining how current practices that imply a degree of 'subordination' - from indentured labour to domestic and ritual servitude - have arisen out of the master-slave relationships of the nineteenth century. In addition, this project will examine how these forms of dependence, generally mediated through kinship structures, are strengthened during periods of economic insecurity in the region. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The recording of experiences of slave-descendents, a greatly under-researched theme in the anthropology of slavery, has formed a key component of this research, with data having been gathered through fieldwork conducted between 2002 and 2008. By examining the strategies developed by some slave-descendents to ensure their inclusion in affairs of the community, this study contradicts the frequently expressed view that these categories of people are unable to contest their marginalisation. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The fellowship will facilitate the publication of journal articles and a monograph&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-08-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>74528</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/H002790/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>EBACD6D4-D1E5-4970-8BEC-7F4568EB26BA</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Development studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>541CDC75-F361-4961-9EFE-34B2C8ACE947</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>History</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>020361E1-B8CA-49FD-9149-27D31D21C7A3</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Anthropology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>32A0976A-B577-4829-A940-9AB6B148F977</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Area &amp; Development Studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>DCE73056-5E3D-4976-B573-234E5FF4D633</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Economic &amp; Social History</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic><gtr:researchTopic><gt